-- ============================================================
-- Enrichment Batch 5B: 30 additional policy ideas
-- Generated: 2026-03-23
-- IDs: 46-50, 52-56, 62-67, 69, 71-78, 81-83, 85-87
-- ============================================================

UPDATE policy_ideas SET description = 'South Africa''s regulated fuel price mechanism, governed by the DMRE, uses a basic fuel price formula based on international benchmarks plus fixed levies and distribution margins. Reform proposals call for partial deregulation of inland retail margins while retaining regulation of the fuel levy and RAF components. The existing single-price model suppresses investment in alternative fuels (LPG, CNG) and new market entrants. The Energy White Paper (2019) and Competition Commission market inquiry (2023) both identified the regulated model as a barrier to efficiency. Parliamentary BRRRs noted the coastal-to-inland cross-subsidy inflates logistics costs for manufacturing and agri-processing. Partial deregulation aligned with the Liquid Fuels Charter is the preferred approach.', feasibility_note = 'Medium. Political sensitivity around petrol prices is high; phased margin deregulation is more achievable than full price liberalisation. Requires amendment to Petroleum Products Act.', responsible_department = 'DMRE / National Treasury', updated_at = datetime('now') WHERE id = 46;

UPDATE policy_ideas SET description = 'South Africa has approximately 6,000 derelict and ownerless mines (DOMs) from the gold and coal eras, posing acid mine drainage, sinkhole, and water pollution risks. The DMRE''s DOM Unit faces a rehabilitation backlog requiring an estimated R50 billion. A dedicated fund—capitalised through mining royalty levies, the Mines and Minerals Development Bill, and potential green bond issuance—would address this fiscal liability systematically. Rand Water''s AMD pumping operation costs R2 billion annually, a preventable outlay if upstream rehabilitation proceeds. Parliamentary BRRRs flagged the Western Basin AMD threat to Johannesburg''s water security repeatedly from 2021 to 2024. International models (US Superfund, Canada''s Abandoned Mines programme) inform the fund design.', feasibility_note = 'Medium. Funding mechanism is contentious—industry opposes retrospective levies. MMDB passage is a prerequisite. Environmental urgency provides political momentum.', responsible_department = 'DMRE / DFFE / National Treasury', updated_at = datetime('now') WHERE id = 47;

UPDATE policy_ideas SET description = 'South Africa''s nuclear build programme—Koeberg Unit 3 planning and IRP 2019 allocation of 2,500 MW of new nuclear—requires the National Nuclear Regulator (NNR) to scale technical oversight capacity for construction, not merely operations. Current NNR staffing is calibrated for Koeberg''s existing two units. Cabinet approved the nuclear procurement programme in 2023. Parliamentary Committee on Mineral Resources BRRRs noted the NNR''s budget has not kept pace with the expanded oversight mandate, risking safety gaps. International partnerships with the IAEA and bilateral agreements with France (EDF) and South Korea (KEPCO) are under active negotiation. The reform involves NNR Act amendment, a staffing plan, and budget increase sufficient to hire and retain nuclear engineers.', feasibility_note = 'Medium-high. NNR is an established institution; scaling is achievable with Treasury allocation. Constraint is specialised nuclear engineering talent availability domestically.', responsible_department = 'DMRE / NNR / DSI', updated_at = datetime('now') WHERE id = 48;

UPDATE policy_ideas SET description = 'NSFAS grew from a R5 billion programme in 2015 to over R47 billion by 2025, absorbing an increasing share of DHET''s budget following the 2017 free higher education announcement. The current model provides non-means-tested free higher education to households below R350,000 annually—fiscally unsustainable and creating perverse incentives. Reform proposals include income-contingent loan repayment for graduates above a threshold, co-payments for middle-income beneficiaries, and an endowment model leveraging private contributions. The Heher Commission (2017) recommended income-contingent loans; Cabinet implemented free HE instead, creating current fiscal pressure. Parliamentary Budget Office analysis shows NSFAS consumes 20% of all education spending. MTBPS 2025 flagged R6 billion in NSFAS irregular expenditure.', feasibility_note = 'Low-medium. Politically charged; any move toward loans is framed as reversing #FeesMustFall gains. Fiscal pressure from audits and budget ceiling may force restructuring.', responsible_department = 'DHET / National Treasury / NSFAS', updated_at = datetime('now') WHERE id = 50;

UPDATE policy_ideas SET description = 'South Africa''s 21 SETAs collect approximately R20 billion annually in Skills Development Levy (1% of payroll) but have been persistently criticised for low disbursement rates, high overhead, and misalignment with industry needs. The DHET-commissioned Ramos Report and Sector Skills Plan reviews all recommend consolidation to 8–10 SETAs, mandatory training outcomes linked to levy disbursement, and greater industry body involvement. Parliamentary Portfolio Committee BRRRs from 2022–2024 documented over R15 billion in unspent SETA reserves and governance failures across multiple SETAs. The Skills Development Act (1998) requires amendment. NQF alignment is a precondition for disbursement reform. EWSETA, merSETA, and AgriSETA have relatively stronger governance and could serve as consolidation anchors.', feasibility_note = 'Medium. Institutional resistance from individual SETAs is strong. Treasury fiscal pressure may accelerate reform; consolidation has been proposed since 2012 with limited progress.', responsible_department = 'DHET / National Treasury', updated_at = datetime('now') WHERE id = 52;

UPDATE policy_ideas SET description = 'South African universities and TVET colleges accumulated a backlog of approximately 350,000 unissued certificates and diplomas in the 2017–2022 period, stemming from NSFAS payment delays withholding transcripts, COVID-related administration disruption, and IEB processing gaps. Unissued certificates prevent graduates from accessing employment and professional registration. The DHET 2023 audit quantified the backlog and proposed a digitisation programme using SAQA''s National Learners'' Records Database (NLRD) as backbone. Key interventions: waiver of outstanding NSFAS debt as a bar to certificate release and automated digital issuance integrated with institutional student systems. The Parliamentary Committee on Higher Education flagged this as a crisis harming graduate employment outcomes annually from 2021 onward.', feasibility_note = 'High. Largely administrative. Requires DHET operational directive, NSFAS debt-transcript policy change, and IT investment. No primary legislation needed.', responsible_department = 'DHET / NSFAS / SAQA', updated_at = datetime('now') WHERE id = 53;

UPDATE policy_ideas SET description = 'South Africa''s gross expenditure on R&D (GERD) stood at approximately 0.56% of GDP in 2023, far below the AU''s 1% target and OECD average of 2.7%. The NDP (2012) set a 1.5% of GDP target by 2030, but business R&D spending has declined relative to government. The DSI''s STI Decadal Plan (2022–2032) outlines investment roadmaps. Section 11D of the Income Tax Act provides a 150% deduction for qualifying R&D—effective in pharmaceuticals and software but under-utilised in mining and manufacturing. Parliamentary Committee on Science and Innovation BRRRs noted government R&D spending fell in real terms from 2019–2024. Achieving 1.5% requires both public appropriation increases and EU Horizon association, which would unlock co-funding for South African researchers.', feasibility_note = 'Medium. Fiscal constraints limit near-term public R&D growth. Tax incentive enhancement and IP commercialisation framework reform are more achievable in the short run.', responsible_department = 'DSI / National Treasury / NRF', updated_at = datetime('now') WHERE id = 54;

UPDATE policy_ideas SET description = 'NSFAS''s administration system has been plagued by fraud, duplicate registrations, and ghost students. A 2023 SIU report identified R5.7 billion in irregular and wasteful expenditure including payments to deregistered students and multiple payments per student. The reform centres on a unified biometric student verification system linked to Home Affairs (DHA) and SAQA''s NLRD, replacing fragmented institution-level verification. A Deloitte/PwC forensic audit (2023) made 42 specific recommendations, most unimplemented. The Parliamentary Committee on Higher Education repeatedly demanded IT system upgrades and forensic audits. The IT modernisation is costed at approximately R800 million over three years. System integration with the Central Application Clearing House (CAO) reduces upstream fraud at the point of application.', feasibility_note = 'High for technical solution; medium for implementation given procurement complexity and resistance from existing scheme administrators.', responsible_department = 'DHET / NSFAS / DHA / SIU', updated_at = datetime('now') WHERE id = 55;

UPDATE policy_ideas SET description = 'South Africa''s Community Education and Training (CET) colleges provide second-chance education for an estimated 3.5 million adults without matric, but enrolments remain under 300,000—far below potential demand. The Second Chance Matric Programme (2017) offers supplementary exams and distance learning for those who failed. The PSET White Paper (2013) envisioned CET as the foundation of a mass adult education system; implementation has been partial. Both programmes are severely underfunded: CET colleges lack infrastructure, qualified educators, and curriculum links to TVET progression pathways. Parliamentary BRRRs noted the absence of articulation between CET, TVET, and university programmes means second-chance learners face dead-end qualifications. Reform requires CET Act amendment, funding model revision, and SAQA articulation framework updates.', feasibility_note = 'Medium. Low political priority relative to universities and NSFAS. Articulation framework improvements have high ROI at low fiscal cost.', responsible_department = 'DHET / DBE / SAQA', updated_at = datetime('now') WHERE id = 56;

UPDATE policy_ideas SET description = 'The National Transmission Company of South Africa (NTCSA), separated from Eskom under the Electricity Regulation Amendment Act (August 2024), requires approximately R100 billion in capitalisation to execute grid expansion absorbing new renewable energy from REIPPPP rounds 6–7 and private embedded generation. Eskom''s transmission grid is at near-capacity; bottlenecks in the Northern Cape (solar) and Eastern Cape (wind) corridors are the primary constraint on new IPP connections. The Energy Transition Investment Plan identifies grid expansion as the critical enabling infrastructure for decarbonisation targets. Parliamentary BRRRs noted the connection queue for new generation projects exceeded 100 GW by 2024, while grid investment had been deferred for 15 years under Eskom''s integrated monopoly structure.', feasibility_note = 'Medium. NTCSA entity is established but funding model—government equity vs. tariff-backed bonds—is unresolved. Requires NERSA tariff approval for cost recovery.', responsible_department = 'DMRE / Eskom/NTCSA / National Treasury', updated_at = datetime('now') WHERE id = 62;

UPDATE policy_ideas SET description = 'Denel, South Africa''s state-owned defence manufacturer, entered financial distress in 2018 following alleged state capture and has required R5.2 billion in government bailouts since 2019. Its capacity to produce ammunition, missile systems, and armoured vehicles—critical to SANDF contracts and export agreements—has been severely compromised. The reform centres on attracting a strategic equity partner (SEP) from India, UAE, Turkey, or an EU member, bringing capital, technology transfer, and production orders. Parliamentary Portfolio Committee on Public Enterprises BRRRs flagged Denel''s pension fund arrears, skills bleed, and inability to fulfil SANDF contracts. South Africa''s National Industrial Participation programme creates counter-investment obligations for defence procurers, providing leverage in an SEP transaction. The Rooivalk helicopter programme demonstrates residual technical capability.', feasibility_note = 'Medium. Residual technical capability exists. Geopolitical positioning (BRICS membership, Western partnerships) complicates partner selection and technology transfer approvals.', responsible_department = 'DPE / ARMSCOR / DOD', updated_at = datetime('now') WHERE id = 63;

UPDATE policy_ideas SET description = 'Alexkor, the state diamond mining company at Alexander Bay, has been entangled in the Richtersveld land restitution claim since 1999. A 2003 Constitutional Court ruling granted the Richtersveld community surface and mineral rights, but the 49% equity settlement has been improperly implemented as Alexkor''s diamond operations collapsed and community trust benefits remain minimal. Safcol (South African Forestry Company) faces restitution claims over commercial forests in Limpopo, Mpumalanga, and KwaZulu-Natal. Both cases represent failure to implement legally settled land claims through workable business models. The reform requires restructuring the Alexkor joint venture, resolving governance between the community trust and mining entity, and processing Safcol community equity models. Parliamentary Committee on Public Enterprises BRRRs flagged both as fiscal risks with governance vacuums.', feasibility_note = 'Medium. Legal settlements exist; implementation is the obstacle. Requires multi-department coordination across DALRRD, DPE, and DPRD.', responsible_department = 'DALRRD / DPE / DPRD', updated_at = datetime('now') WHERE id = 64;

UPDATE policy_ideas SET description = 'South African Airways entered business rescue in December 2019 and emerged in April 2021 after R10.5 billion in government funding. The relaunched SAA operated limited routes from September 2021, but the Takatso Consortium 51% private equity deal collapsed in 2024. The MTBPS 2025 framework explicitly flagged further SAA recapitalisation as unaffordable. Options include full privatisation, merger with Airlink, or structured wind-down. Parliamentary Committee on Public Enterprises BRRRs documented SAA''s cost structure remaining misaligned with the competitive African aviation market dominated by Ethiopian Airlines and Kenya Airways. The Competition Commission airline market study (2023) provided market structure context. Political symbolism of a national carrier remains the primary constraint on commercially rational decision-making.', feasibility_note = 'Low for continued state support; medium-high for privatisation or structured wind-down. Treasury fiscal pressure is the primary driver of reform urgency.', responsible_department = 'DPE / National Treasury / SAA', updated_at = datetime('now') WHERE id = 65;

UPDATE policy_ideas SET description = 'The Technology Innovation Agency (TIA), established under the DSI in 2008, provides bridge funding between academic research and commercial scale-up with an annual budget of approximately R900 million. TIA has supported over 200 companies, but its commercialisation success rate—measured by IP licences, spinouts reaching revenue, and jobs created—is below international benchmarks. Reform involves restructuring TIA''s mandate to focus on fewer, larger bets aligned with DSI''s priority sectors (green hydrogen, mining automation, health biotech), introducing co-investment requirements from industry and VC co-investors, and improving portfolio monitoring. Parliamentary Committee on Science and Innovation BRRRs noted TIA''s administrative overhead absorbs 25–30% of budget and that portfolio attrition rates are high relative to comparators like Israel''s BIRD Foundation.', feasibility_note = 'High. Administrative reform within DSI''s mandate. Budget reorientation does not require legislation; TIA Act amendment only needed if mandate changes substantially.', responsible_department = 'DSI / TIA / dtic', updated_at = datetime('now') WHERE id = 66;

UPDATE policy_ideas SET description = 'The IPR-PFRD Act (2008), modelled on the US Bayh-Dole Act, governs how IP developed from public R&D funding is commercialised. The National Intellectual Property Management Office (NIPMO) within DSI implements the Act but has been underfunded and understaffed. Key obstacles are mandatory government march-in rights provisions deterring private co-investors, complex disclosure timelines (36 months), and NIPMO''s limited capacity for international patent applications. Reform proposals include streamlining the commercialisation timeline to 12 months, removing automatic government retention for non-national-security IP, and co-funding international patent filing through the NRF''s IP Fund. A NIPMO Amendment Bill was introduced in Parliament in 2023 but not passed. Industry support for reform is strong; government march-in rights are the political sticking point.', feasibility_note = 'Medium. Requires IPR-PFRD Act amendment. Industry support strong. Government retention provision is the key negotiating obstacle with the Presidency and NIPMO.', responsible_department = 'DSI / NIPMO / dtic', updated_at = datetime('now') WHERE id = 67;

UPDATE policy_ideas SET description = 'South Africa''s STI Decadal Plan, gazetted in 2022, sets 10-year targets across eight priority areas: space, the ocean economy, advanced manufacturing, agriculture, human health, energy, ICT, and mining. The Plan is the most ambitious STI policy framework since the 1996 White Paper. However, it remains largely unfunded: the MTBPS 2025 did not allocate the estimated R50 billion required for full implementation, and DSI''s budget has declined in real terms. Parliamentary Committee on Science and Innovation BRRRs noted the disconnect between the Decadal Plan''s ambition and DSI''s appropriation trajectory. The reform converts the Decadal Plan into a funded mandate through multi-year appropriations, EU Horizon association co-funding, AfDB grants, and revised CSIR/NRF mandates explicitly aligned to Decadal Plan priorities.', feasibility_note = 'Medium. Fiscal constraints are the main barrier. Phased implementation targeting 2-3 high-impact priority areas is more achievable than full-plan funding in the current MTBPS environment.', responsible_department = 'DSI / National Treasury / NRF / CSIR', updated_at = datetime('now') WHERE id = 69;

UPDATE policy_ideas SET description = 'The CSIR, South Africa''s primary applied research institution with 3,000+ researchers and R3.5 billion in annual revenue, is proposed as the anchor institution for a 10-year foundational digital capabilities programme covering AI model development, cybersecurity, quantum computing, and advanced semiconductor design. The programme mirrors Singapore''s A*STAR and Germany''s Fraunhofer Society, where public research institutes provide industry-connective tissue for digital transformation. The Presidential Commission on the Fourth Industrial Revolution (2019) and DSI''s 4IR Initiative both identified CSIR as the natural lead. Parliamentary Committee on Science and Innovation BRRRs noted CSIR''s external industry revenue has increased but foundational R&D is crowded out by short-term commercialisation pressure, eroding the long-term research pipeline.', feasibility_note = 'Medium. Requires dedicated budget allocation and ring-fencing of foundational research from revenue-generating activities. CSIR governance reform may be a prerequisite.', responsible_department = 'DSI / CSIR / dtic', updated_at = datetime('now') WHERE id = 71;

UPDATE policy_ideas SET description = 'The NRF funds approximately 30,000 postgraduate students annually but bursary values of R80,000–R120,000 for doctoral students in 2024 are insufficient for urban cost of living and uncompetitive with international programmes, contributing to brain drain. Reform proposals include doubling doctoral bursary values to R180,000–R250,000, introducing industry co-funding requirements for applied research areas (mining, fintech, agri-tech), and linking bursary allocations to DSI Decadal Plan priorities. The NRF Amendment Act (2019) created the framework for industry partnerships; implementation has been partial. Parliamentary Committee on Science BRRRs noted South Africa''s PhD production rate of 45 per million population is below the AU target of 100 per million by 2025, with bursary inadequacy as a cited cause of slow growth.', feasibility_note = 'High. Bursary value increase is a budget line item within DSI/NRF appropriations. Industry co-funding leverages the existing Section 11D R&D tax incentive framework.', responsible_department = 'DSI / NRF / DHET', updated_at = datetime('now') WHERE id = 72;

UPDATE policy_ideas SET description = 'South Africa''s agricultural sector contributes 2.5% of GDP while employing 5.5% of the workforce, yet underperforms its potential in technology adoption. Precision agriculture, digital market linkage platforms, cold chain logistics, and agro-processing value addition are underdeveloped relative to Brazil, Kenya, and the Netherlands. The Agri-Tech cluster reform proposes concentrating agri-tech incubation, R&D, and production in SEZs in the Western Cape (wine and horticulture), Limpopo (tropical fruits), and KwaZulu-Natal (sugar and macadamia). DAFF''s Agri-Parks programme provides partial infrastructure. Parliamentary Committee on Agriculture BRRRs noted the R14 billion agriculture budget is heavily weighted toward land reform rather than productivity enhancement. DTIC''s SEZ framework provides the legal and incentive structure for cluster development.', feasibility_note = 'Medium. SEZ model has precedent. Policy coordination across DTIC, DAFF, and DSI is the key implementation risk; private sector investment is the primary funding mechanism.', responsible_department = 'DTIC / DAFF / DSI', updated_at = datetime('now') WHERE id = 73;

UPDATE policy_ideas SET description = 'South Africa''s space programme through SANSA has a legacy in Earth observation and space weather monitoring but limited commercial satellite manufacturing or launch services. The DSI Space Economy Roadmap (2017) and STI Decadal Plan target R21 billion in space economy value and 10,000 jobs by 2030. Geographic positioning near optimal orbital inclinations and the residual capability of Denel Spaceteq offer a foundation for a commercial satellite manufacturing hub. Reform involves establishing a commercial space agency framework, amending the Space Affairs Act (1993), and attracting anchor tenants for a proposed satellite manufacturing cluster at the Cape Peninsula. ESA, NASA, and commercial launch provider partnerships (including Starlink ground operations) are identified leverage points. Parliamentary Committee on Science BRRRs noted SANSA''s budget is insufficient for commercial programme development.', feasibility_note = 'Medium. Legislative framework update needed. Capital requirements are substantial and international partnerships are essential to de-risk initial investments.', responsible_department = 'DSI / SANSA / DMRE', updated_at = datetime('now') WHERE id = 74;

UPDATE policy_ideas SET description = 'South Africa is signatory to the CBD and Nagoya Protocol, requiring formal access and benefit-sharing (ABS) frameworks for commercialising indigenous knowledge systems (IKS) in biodiversity products and traditional medicine. The IP Laws Amendment Act (2013) created an IKS database through CIPC, but implementation has been slow. The rooibos ABS agreement (2019), which secured R1.5 million in annual payments to San and Khoikhoi communities, provides a working model. The Hoodia cactus case illustrated biopiracy risks where SA failed to protect community interests. The DSI''s revised IKS Policy (2023) needs legislative backing through the Traditional Knowledge Bill, in draft since 2017. Parliamentary Committee on Trade and Industry BRRRs noted the backlog of IKS protection cases and the absence of a funded NIPMO-equivalent for traditional knowledge management.', feasibility_note = 'Medium. Rooibos case provides a working model. Legislative bottleneck is the unpassed Traditional Knowledge Bill. DSI and dtic coordination and CIPC capacity are needed.', responsible_department = 'DSI / dtic / DALRRD / CIPC', updated_at = datetime('now') WHERE id = 75;

UPDATE policy_ideas SET description = 'PRASA suffered catastrophic infrastructure deterioration during the COVID-19 lockdown, with rolling stock theft reaching R13 billion in asset losses. By 2022, fewer than 20% of planned services were operating. The Recovery Plan launched under a new PRASA Board in 2022 targets restoring 80% of pre-2019 service levels, deploying X''Trapolis Mega rolling stock (manufactured by Gibela Rail under a local content agreement), and rehabilitating priority corridors in Cape Town, Johannesburg, Pretoria, and Durban. The MTBPS 2025 allocated R25 billion for PRASA recapitalisation over three years. Parliamentary Committee on Transport BRRRs documented the scale of signal system, overhead traction equipment, and station facility damage and the governance failures that enabled the deterioration under the previous PRASA board.', feasibility_note = 'Medium-high. Recovery plan has political support and dedicated funding. Execution risk is high given PRASA''s procurement capacity constraints and the depth of infrastructure damage.', responsible_department = 'Department of Transport / PRASA / DPWI', updated_at = datetime('now') WHERE id = 76;

UPDATE policy_ideas SET description = 'The Economic Regulation of Transport (EROT) Act, signed in 2024, establishes South Africa''s first independent transport economic regulator covering freight rail, ports, pipelines, and public transport tariffs. The regulator consolidates functions previously fragmented across the Ports Regulator, NERSA (pipelines), and PRASA. Operationalising EROT requires board and executive appointments, office establishment, methodology guidelines, and function transfers from existing regulators—estimated at 24 months. Parliamentary Committee on Transport BRRRs noted the absence of independent economic regulation enabled Transnet to cross-subsidise loss-making services with freight rail revenue, distorting pricing signals for private operators. The regulator''s independence from the Department of Transport is a key design principle drawn from the NERSA model. Treasury''s independent institutions framework governs its fiscal relationship.', feasibility_note = 'High. Legislative basis is established. Board appointments and budget allocation are the near-term deliverables. Institutional design risks (scope creep, regulatory capture) require careful governance.', responsible_department = 'Department of Transport / National Treasury / EROT', updated_at = datetime('now') WHERE id = 77;

UPDATE policy_ideas SET description = 'The Road Accident Fund (RAF) has accumulated a deficit exceeding R600 billion—the largest contingent liability on the South African state balance sheet—through unlimited general damages liability, R5 billion annually in legal costs, and inadequate fuel levy revenue. The Road Accident Benefit Scheme (RABS), proposed since 2008, would replace the current common-law third-party liability system with a no-fault administratively managed benefit schedule, similar to New Zealand''s ACC. RABS has been before Parliament since 2018; opposition from the plaintiff attorney bar (earning R10+ billion annually from RAF litigation) has stalled passage. Parliamentary Committee on Transport BRRRs from 2021–2024 consistently ranked RAF reform as the single largest fiscal risk in the transport portfolio, with the deficit growing by approximately R60 billion annually.', feasibility_note = 'Low-medium due to legal industry opposition. Actuarial case for RABS is overwhelming. Political will exists in Treasury; Parliamentary timetable is the binding constraint.', responsible_department = 'Department of Transport / RAF / National Treasury / DOJ', updated_at = datetime('now') WHERE id = 78;

UPDATE policy_ideas SET description = 'SANRAL lost its user-pay funding model when Gauteng e-tolling was abolished in April 2022 following sustained civil resistance, leaving R43 billion in GFIP debt transferred to government. SANRAL''s non-toll road network (26,000+ km) now relies entirely on Parliamentary appropriation, insufficient to maintain the asset base: the maintenance backlog exceeds R30 billion. Reform centres on a sustainable alternative road funding model—vehicle kilometres travelled tax, annual road-user charge, or fuel levy increase—to replace e-tolling without repeating its political failure. National Treasury''s 2023 discussion paper modelled five alternatives. Parliamentary Committee on Transport BRRRs noted SANRAL''s credit rating implications of the government guarantee on GFIP debt, constraining its borrowing capacity for future road investment.', feasibility_note = 'Medium. Fiscal necessity is driving urgency. Any user-pay mechanism faces the e-toll precedent; a fuel levy increase (R0.20/litre) is politically the path of least resistance.', responsible_department = 'SANRAL / Department of Transport / National Treasury', updated_at = datetime('now') WHERE id = 81;

UPDATE policy_ideas SET description = 'The Railway Safety Regulator (RSR), established under the National Railway Safety Regulator Act (2002), oversees all railway operators across approximately 23,000 km of track—including Transnet Freight Rail, PRASA, and private industrial railways—but is persistently underfunded relative to its mandate. The RSR has fewer than 200 inspectors for the full network. PRASA train collision incidents (Kempton Park 2018, Cape Town 2019) and Transnet locomotive failure patterns highlighted the RSR''s limited investigative capacity. Reform involves increasing the RSR''s budget, granting independent enforcement powers parallel to the NERSA model, and mandating independent accident investigation through an AIIB-style board separate from the RSR itself. Parliamentary Committee on Transport BRRRs noted the RSR cannot effectively enforce compliance against large state operators like Transnet, which has a self-interest in minimising regulatory intervention.', feasibility_note = 'High. Administrative and budgetary reform within existing legislative framework. Political resistance from Transnet is manageable given public safety imperatives.', responsible_department = 'Department of Transport / RSR / PRASA / Transnet', updated_at = datetime('now') WHERE id = 82;

UPDATE policy_ideas SET description = 'South Africa''s minibus taxi industry transports approximately 16 million commuters daily—more than all other public transport modes combined—yet operates almost entirely outside formal regulation, subsidy, and safety frameworks. The industry contributes an estimated R90 billion to GDP but generates R15 billion in annual economic losses through accidents, route violence, and inefficiency. Integrated Public Transport Networks (IPTNs) have begun integrating taxis through negotiated contracts in Cape Town. Digital integration—NATIS vehicle registration linked to operator permits, e-hailing platform interfaces, and digital fare payment—is the core operational reform alongside operator permit formalisation. Parliamentary Committee on Transport BRRRs noted NLTA amendment is needed to provide the legal basis for taxi contracting under IPTN frameworks. SANTACO and the NTA are organised industry stakeholders with legitimate interests requiring accommodation.', feasibility_note = 'Medium. Taxi associations are organised and politically connected. Violence risk during route rationalisation is the principal constraint; phased digital integration is lower risk.', responsible_department = 'Department of Transport / dtic / COGTA', updated_at = datetime('now') WHERE id = 83;

UPDATE policy_ideas SET description = 'South Africa''s 3,900 km coastline, two major ocean trade routes, and five commercial ports give it strategic maritime importance, yet the merchant shipping and maritime industry remains underdeveloped. South Africa has no meaningful cabotage policy, limited maritime training capacity through SAMSA''s SA Maritime Training Academy, and few SA-flagged vessels. Operation Phakisa''s Oceans Economy roadmap and the 2050 Maritime Industry Master Plan identified merchant shipping development as a priority. Reform includes a cabotage policy for coastal trade (reserving coastal cargo for SA-flagged vessels), SAMSA Act amendment to strengthen port state control, and expansion of the Simon''s Town and Durban maritime clusters. Parliamentary Committee on Transport BRRRs noted SAMSA''s budget is insufficient to enforce port state control effectively, undermining safety and competitive standards at SA ports.', feasibility_note = 'Medium. Operation Phakisa provides institutional momentum. Cabotage policy requires customs alignment. Domestic shipping industry too small to generate strong political advocacy.', responsible_department = 'Department of Transport / SAMSA / dtic / Ports Regulator', updated_at = datetime('now') WHERE id = 85;

UPDATE policy_ideas SET description = 'The BELA Act, signed by President Ramaphosa in September 2024, shifts language and admissions policy authority from school governing bodies (SGBs) to provincial education departments and makes Grade R compulsory. Key implementation challenges include DBE capacity to manage SGB authority transitions, language policy disputes in Western Cape Afrikaans-medium schools (with Constitutional Court challenges signalled by Afriforum and Freedom Front Plus), and Grade R infrastructure requirements of approximately 15,000 additional classrooms. Parliamentary Committee on Basic Education BRRRs noted the DBE''s implementation plan requires R8 billion over three years for Grade R infrastructure. Teacher qualification requirements for Grade R ECD practitioners and the articulation between BELA''s Grade R provisions and the ECD function shift (id=87) are the key inter-departmental coordination challenges.', feasibility_note = 'Medium. Act is passed; implementation is the challenge. Language policy litigation will delay certain provisions. Grade R compulsion requires significant capital investment before it can be enforced.', responsible_department = 'DBE / DPWI / National Treasury', updated_at = datetime('now') WHERE id = 86;

UPDATE policy_ideas SET description = 'The transfer of Early Childhood Development (ECD) from DSD to DBE, executed in 2022, was the largest single function shift in post-1994 South African government. Approximately 47,000 ECD centres (mostly community-based and NGO-operated), 22,000 practitioners, and 900,000 children under 6 were transferred. Implementation challenges include subsidy payment system migration from DSD''s SOCPEN to DBE''s payment systems, practitioner qualification upgrades to NQF Level 4 minimum, infrastructure standards compliance, and municipal zoning for ECD centres. DBE''s conditional ECD grant (R1.4 billion in 2025/26) is insufficient for the full infrastructure backlog. Parliamentary Committee on Basic Education BRRRs noted the function shift created a registration gap for many centres awaiting DBE systems, temporarily cutting subsidy payments and threatening centre viability.', feasibility_note = 'Medium. Function shift is legally complete. Implementation quality determines child outcomes. DBE''s administrative capacity (DPSA-constrained) is the primary execution risk.', responsible_department = 'DBE / DSD / National Treasury / DPSA', updated_at = datetime('now') WHERE id = 87;
